<div style="background-color:#000000;clear:both;height:2pt;page-break-after:always;width:79.3%;border:0;margin:30pt 10.35% 30pt 10.35%;"></div><div style="max-width:100%;padding-left:10.35%;padding-right:10.35%;position:relative;"><div style="margin-top:21.6pt;min-height:41.75pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;margin:0pt 0pt 30pt 0pt;"><a href="#Toc"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;line-height:1.43;text-align:left;">Table of Contents</span></a></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;text-align:center;margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">AVNET, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES<br />NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS<br />(unaudited)</b></p></div><div style="clear:both;max-width:100%;position:relative;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><a id="Notes_to_Consolidated_Financial_Statemen"></a><a id="bm_1_Basis_of_presentation"></a><a id="_Hlk22729601"></a><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="avt:BasisOfPresentationAndNewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyTextBlock" id="Tb_gP45iewMp0SDLe4sbxoJzA" continuedAt="Tb_gP45iewMp0SDLe4sbxoJzA_cont1" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">1. Basis of presentation and new </b><b style="font-weight:bold;">accounting </b><b style="font-weight:bold;">pronouncements</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:BasisOfAccountingPolicyPolicyTextBlock" id="Tb_MjZn-M2gJECU9-SEBD_kXg" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">In the opinion of management, the accompanying unaudited interim consolidated financial statements contain all adjustments necessary to present fairly Avnet, Inc. and its consolidated subsidiaries&#8217; (collectively, the &#8220;Company&#8221; or &#8220;Avnet&#8221;) financial position, results of operations, comprehensive income and cash flows. All such adjustments are of a normal recurring nature.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;) requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the amounts reported in the consolidated financial statements. Actual results may differ from these estimates.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">Interim results of operations are not necessarily indicative of the results to be expected for the full fiscal year. The information included in this Form 10-Q should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and accompanying notes included in the Company&#8217;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the fiscal year ended June 29, 2019.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">Certain reclassifications have been made in prior periods to conform to the current period presentation.</p></ix:nonNumeric><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:NewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyPolicyTextBlock" id="Tb_4dT5hEUsNkqoCEQMlb4b2Q" continuedAt="Tb_4dT5hEUsNkqoCEQMlb4b2Q_cont1" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><i style="font-style:italic;">Recently adopted accounting pronouncements</i></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company adopted Accounting Standards Update (&#8220;ASU&#8221;) No. 2016-02, <i style="font-style:italic;">&#8220;Leases (Topic 842),&#8221;</i> and its related amendments (collectively &#8220;ASC 842&#8221;) on June 30, 2019 (the first day of fiscal 2020) using the modified transition approach without restating the comparative period consolidated financial statements. The standard requires lessees to recognize a right-of-use asset and a short-term and long-term lease liability for all leases.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"> <span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The adoption of ASC 842 did not have a material impact on the Company&#8217;s consolidated statements of operations or retained earnings. The Company elected the <ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" format="ixt:booleantrue" name="us-gaap:LeasePracticalExpedientsPackage" id="Narr_dmhlbY2ZtE6nUFy9XPoCCQ">package of practical expedients</ix:nonNumeric> permitted under the transition guidance that allowed, among other things, the historical lease classification to be carried forward without reassessment and the <ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" format="ixt:booleantrue" name="us-gaap:LeasePracticalExpedientUseOfHindsight" id="Narr_nlna4E_cEECRsvciFaiaUA">hindsight</ix:nonNumeric> practical expedient. The Company elected to not separate lease and non-lease components for its real estate leases. Refer to Note 5 for additional disclosures related to leases.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">In August 2017, the FASB issued ASU No. 2017-12, <i style="font-style:italic;">Derivatives and Hedging (Topic 815) - Targeted Improvements to Accounting for Hedging Activities&#8221; </i>and its related amendments (collectively &#8220;ASC 815&#8221;), which improves the financial reporting of hedging relationships to better portray the economic results of an entity&#8217;s risk management activities in its financial statements and makes certain targeted improvements to simplify the qualification and application of hedge accounting compared to historical GAAP. This update is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2018, with early adoption permitted. The adoption of ASC 815 in the first quarter of fiscal 2020 did not have an impact on the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><i style="font-style:italic;">Recently issued accounting pronouncements</i></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">In December 2019, the FASB issued ASU No. 2019-12, <i style="font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Accounting for Income Taxes</i> <i style="font-style:italic;">(Topic 740)</i>, which removes certain exceptions to the general principles in Topic 740 and also clarifies and amends existing guidance to improve consistent application. The ASU will be effective for the Company in the first quarter of fiscal 2022, and early adoption is permitted. Depending on the amendment, adoption may be applied on the retrospective, modified retrospective or prospective basis. The Company is currently evaluating the potential effects of adopting the provisions of ASU No. 2019-12.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></ix:nonNumeric></ix:nonNumeric></div><div style="clear:both;margin-bottom:30pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">7</p></div></div>
<div style="background-color:#000000;clear:both;height:2pt;page-break-after:always;width:79.3%;border:0;margin:30pt 10.35% 30pt 10.35%;"></div><div style="max-width:100%;padding-left:10.35%;padding-right:10.35%;position:relative;"><div style="margin-top:21.6pt;min-height:41.75pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;margin:0pt 0pt 30pt 0pt;"><a href="#Toc"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;line-height:1.43;text-align:left;">Table of Contents</span></a></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;text-align:center;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">AVNET, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;text-align:center;margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS - (Continued)</b></p></div><div style="clear:both;max-width:100%;position:relative;"><ix:continuation id="Tb_gP45iewMp0SDLe4sbxoJzA_cont1"><ix:continuation id="Tb_4dT5hEUsNkqoCEQMlb4b2Q_cont1"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">In August 2018, the FASB issued ASU No. 2018-15, <i style="font-style:italic;">Intangibles&#8212;Goodwill and Other&#8212; Internal-Use Software</i> <i style="font-style:italic;">(Subtopic 350-40):</i> <i style="font-style:italic;">Customer&#8217;s Accounting for Implementation Costs Incurred in a Cloud Computing Arrangement That Is a Service Contract (a consensus of the FASB Emerging Issues Task Force)</i> (&quot;ASU No. 2018-15&quot;). ASU No. 2018-15 aligns the requirements for capitalizing implementation costs incurred in a hosting arrangement that is a service contract with the requirements for capitalizing implementation costs incurred to develop internal-use software. ASU No. 2018-15 is effective for the Company in the first quarter of fiscal 2021, with early adoption permitted, and is to be applied either retrospectively or prospectively. The Company is currently evaluating the potential effects of adopting the provisions of ASU No. 2018-15.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">In August 2018, the FASB issued ASU No. 2018-14, <i style="font-style:italic;">Compensation-Retirement Benefits-Defined Benefit Plans-General (Subtopic 715-20): Disclosure Framework-Changes to the Disclosure Requirements for Defined Benefit Plans</i> (&#8220;ASU No. 2018-14&#8221;). The new guidance modifies the disclosure requirements for employers that sponsor defined benefit pension or other postretirement plans, including removing certain previous disclosure requirements, adding certain new disclosure requirements, and clarifying certain other disclosure requirements. The ASU will be effective for the Company in the first quarter of fiscal 2022, and early adoption is permitted. The Company&#8217;s planned adoption of ASU No. 2018-14 is not expected to have an impact on the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">In June 2016, the FASB issued ASU No. 2016-13, <i style="font-style:italic;">Financial Instruments - Credit Losses (Topic 326): Measurement of Credit Losses on Financial Instruments</i> (&quot;ASU No. 2016-13&quot;) and also issued subsequent amendments to the initial guidance: ASU No. 2018-19, ASU No. 2019-04, ASU No. 2019-05, and ASU No. 2019-11 (collectively, Topic 326). Topic 326 revises the methodology for measuring credit losses on financial instruments and the timing of when such losses are recorded. Topic 326 is effective for the Company in the first quarter of fiscal 2021, with early adoption permitted, and is to be applied using a modified retrospective approach. The company is currently evaluating the potential effects of adopting the provisions of ASU No. 2016-13.</p></ix:continuation><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></ix:continuation><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="avt:BusinessAcquisitionsAndDisposalGroupIncludingDiscontinuedOperationsTextBlock" id="Tb_oCpgOoZyjkKJ6Wwpscdbiw" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">2. Acquisitions and discontinued operations</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><i style="font-style:italic;">Acquisitions</i></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">During the second quarter of fiscal 2020, the Company completed <ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_item_HrO76sMrwU6xg4DxVhKQtA" contextRef="Duration_9_29_2019_To_12_28_2019_FcUSeILTSU6ichjtcZQsfA" decimals="INF" format="ixt-sec:numwordsen" name="us-gaap:NumberOfBusinessesAcquired" scale="0" id="Narr_9cEObQv7k0Kt9HtxGcjzTQ">two</ix:nonFraction> acquisitions. The impact of these acquisitions was not material to the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheets or statements of operations and as a result, the Company has not disclosed the preliminary allocation of purchase price or the pro-forma impact of the acquisition.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><i style="font-style:italic;">Discontinued Operations</i></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">In February 2017, the Company completed the sale of its Technology Solutions business (&#8220;TS business&#8221;) to Tech Data Corporation (the &#8220;Buyer&#8221;). The TS business and the financial impacts of the divestiture are classified as discontinued operations in all periods presented. In August 2018, the Company executed a settlement agreement with the Buyer resulting in a final sales price increase of $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_us-gaap_DisposalGroupClassificationAxis_us-gaap_DisposalGroupDisposedOfBySaleNotDiscontinuedOperationsMember_us-gaap_IncomeStatementBalanceSheetAndAdditionalDisclosuresByDisposalGroupsIncludingDiscontinuedOperationsAxis_avt_TsBusinessMember_rjUyPVDd-0GaBM1jiMSeoQ" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="avt:DisposalGroupIncludingDiscontinuedOperationFinalClosingAdjustment" scale="6" id="Narr_L0Q5FZNlq0WKU3SmjMhBiA">120.0</ix:nonFraction> million and a final geographic allocation of the TS business sales price for tax reporting purposes. This incremental consideration received from the sale of the TS business as well as cash settlements from the resolution of indemnification claims and other cash reimbursements have been classified as cash flows from discontinued operations investing activities. Income tax payments related to the gain on sale of the TS business have been classified as cash flows from discontinued operations operating activities.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">Under the contractual terms of the sale of the TS business, the Company has indemnified the Buyer for certain liabilities including tax related matters, which may result in future indemnification expenses and indemnification payments to the Buyer depending upon the outcome of those matters subject to indemnification.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></ix:nonNumeric><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-size:1pt;font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></div><div style="clear:both;margin-bottom:30pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">8</p></div></div>

style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company evaluates each quarter if facts and circumstances indicate that it is more likely than not that the fair value of its reporting units is less than their carrying value, which would require the Company to perform an interim goodwill impairment test. Indicators the Company evaluates to determine whether an interim goodwill impairment test is necessary include, but are not limited to, (i) a sustained decrease in share price or market capitalization as of any fiscal quarter end, (ii) changes in macroeconomic or industry environments, (iii) the results of and the amount of time passed since the last goodwill impairment test and (iv) the long-term expected financial performance of its reporting units.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">Bank credit facilities and other consists primarily of various committed and uncommitted lines of credit and other forms of bank debt with financial institutions utilized primarily to support the working capital requirements of the Company including its foreign operations.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company has a trade accounts receivable securitization program (the &#8220;Securitization Program&#8221;) in the United States with a group of financial institutions to allow the Company to transfer, on an ongoing revolving basis, an undivided interest in a designated pool of trade accounts receivable, to provide security or collateral for borrowings up to a maximum of $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_us-gaap_DebtInstrumentAxis_avt_AccountsReceivableSecuritizationProgramMember_us-gaap_LongtermDebtTypeAxis_us-gaap_RevolvingCreditFacilityMember_P6nbJeP1wUqrJmHOCic4Ng" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:LineOfCreditFacilityMaximumBorrowingCapacity" scale="6" id="Narr_SEmlIbe4cEufVvqjEa62gA">500</ix:nonFraction> million. The Securitization Program does not qualify for off balance sheet accounting treatment and any borrowings under the Securitization Program are recorded as debt in the consolidated balance sheets. Under the Securitization Program, the Company legally sells and isolates certain U.S. trade accounts receivable into a wholly owned and consolidated bankruptcy remote special purpose entity. Such receivables, which are recorded within &#8220;Receivables&#8221; in the consolidated balance sheets, totaled $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_us-gaap_DebtInstrumentAxis_avt_AccountsReceivableSecuritizationProgramMember_us-gaap_LongtermDebtTypeAxis_us-gaap_RevolvingCreditFacilityMember_P6nbJeP1wUqrJmHOCic4Ng" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:AccountsReceivableFromSecuritization" scale="6" id="Narr_Rxrp0hVKIEK5soaWvI0_4g">740.8</ix:nonFraction> million and $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_6_29_2019_us-gaap_DebtInstrumentAxis_avt_AccountsReceivableSecuritizationProgramMember_us-gaap_LongtermDebtTypeAxis_us-gaap_RevolvingCreditFacilityMember_GmXJkKHLV0C5RmxABtmPpg" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:AccountsReceivableFromSecuritization" scale="6" id="Narr_jTXYD2Ed4UOMNaLqJQQSog">857.3</ix:nonFraction> million at December 28, 2019 and June 29, 2019, respectively. The Securitization Program contains certain covenants relating to the quality of the receivables sold. The Securitization Program also requires the Company to maintain certain minimum interest coverage and leverage ratios, which the Company was in compliance with as of December 28, 2019, and June 29, 2019. The Securitization Program expires in August 2020 and as a result the Company has classified outstanding balances as short-term debt as of December 28, 2019. Interest on borrowings is calculated using a one-month LIBOR rate plus a spread of <ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_pure_ROOYQs8DH0SppyZa338AWA" contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_us-gaap_DebtInstrumentAxis_avt_AccountsReceivableSecuritizationProgramMember_us-gaap_LongtermDebtTypeAxis_us-gaap_RevolvingCreditFacilityMember_us-gaap_VariableRateAxis_us-gaap_LondonInterbankOfferedRateLIBORMember_SXCmtmsEXki5dxoJaHcZCg" decimals="4" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:DebtInstrumentBasisSpreadOnVariableRate1" scale="-2" id="Narr_Jlpdg5oxtEaiDJZz1DDz-A">0.75</ix:nonFraction>%. As of December 28, 2019, and June 29, 2019, there were $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_us-gaap_DebtInstrumentAxis_us-gaap_LineOfCreditMember_us-gaap_LongtermDebtTypeAxis_us-gaap_LetterOfCreditMember_ZnDCfCVs5UKT_FEuApxk9A" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:LettersOfCreditOutstandingAmount" scale="6" id="Narr_RpwIAhCnTESnZa5AwHeMdw">3.9</ix:nonFraction> million and $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_6_29_2019_us-gaap_DebtInstrumentAxis_us-gaap_LineOfCreditMember_us-gaap_LongtermDebtTypeAxis_us-gaap_LetterOfCreditMember_wCSR35SV00yxKQeo7Th0ZA" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:LettersOfCreditOutstandingAmount" scale="6" id="Narr_S7s38Af6rUOyJduExyhSLg">4.0</ix:nonFraction> million, respectively, in letters of credit issued under the Credit Facility.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">As of December 28, 2019, the carrying value and fair value of the Company&#8217;s total debt was $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_qrFIt1ADfEaVVPvPLTg9-w" decimals="-7" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:DebtLongtermAndShorttermCombinedAmount" scale="9" id="Narr_aRLoLAq8ekaiMRVX0--9Sw">1.69</ix:nonFraction> billion and $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_qrFIt1ADfEaVVPvPLTg9-w" decimals="-7" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:DebtInstrumentFairValue" scale="9" id="Narr_wKj7InoUK0KAfnVJcGqtzg">1.76</ix:nonFraction> billion, respectively. At June 29, 2019, the carrying value and fair value of the Company&#8217;s total debt was $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_6_29_2019_R1AOniZLZEq7MnH0mIe5cg" decimals="-7" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:DebtLongtermAndShorttermCombinedAmount" scale="9" id="Narr_684XglLJP0uWOTi1lxMpkQ">1.72</ix:nonFraction> billion and $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_6_29_2019_R1AOniZLZEq7MnH0mIe5cg" decimals="-7" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:DebtInstrumentFairValue" scale="9" id="Narr_pJF4C3ZYCkm9LV0LlVuAzA">1.78</ix:nonFraction> billion, respectively. Fair value for the public notes was estimated based upon quoted market prices and for other forms of debt fair value approximates carrying value due to the market based variable nature of the interest rates on those debt facilities.</p></ix:continuation><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:LesseeOperatingLeasesTextBlock" id="Tb_oZglyDAWWE-j1eOWH3kGgA" continuedAt="Tb_oZglyDAWWE-j1eOWH3kGgA_cont1" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">5. Leases</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">Substantially all the Company&#8217;s leases are classified as operating leases and are predominately related to real property for distribution centers, office space and integration facilities with a lease term of up to <ix:nonNumeric contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_srt_RangeAxis_srt_MaximumMember_BhKjX00s6k2CEOKTXR2vuA" format="ixt-sec:durwordsen" name="us-gaap:LesseeOperatingLeaseTermOfContract" id="Narr_9BLRN7HNkku25VpzgJVITQ">18 years</ix:nonNumeric>. The Company&#8217;s equipment leases are primarily for automobiles and equipment and are not material to the consolidated financial statements.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company determines if an arrangement contains a lease at inception based on whether it conveys the right to control the use of an identified asset in exchange for consideration. Lease right-of-use assets (&#8220;operating lease assets&#8221;) and associated liabilities (&#8220;operating lease liabilities&#8221;) are recognized at the commencement date of the lease based on the present value of lease payments over the lease term. Certain lease agreements may include one or more options to extend or terminate a lease. Lease terms are inclusive of these options if it is reasonably certain that the Company will exercise such options. </p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></ix:nonNumeric></div><div style="clear:both;margin-bottom:30pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">11</p></div></div>

id="Tc_WS4mLwGEJkymEcUUNfXTBA_3_3"></a><ix:continuation id="Tb_oZglyDAWWE-j1eOWH3kGgA_cont1" continuedAt="Tb_oZglyDAWWE-j1eOWH3kGgA_cont2"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company&#8217;s leases generally do not provide a readily determinable implicit borrowing rate, as such, the discount rate used to calculate present value is based upon an estimate of the Company&#8217;s secured borrowing rate. The estimated secured borrowing rates used at the date of adoption for each lease varies in accordance with the lease term and the currency of the lease payments. Lease cost is recognized on a straight-line basis over the lease term and is included as a component of &#8220;Selling, general, and administrative expenses&#8221; in the consolidated statements of operations. Lease payments are primarily fixed; however, certain lease agreements contain variable payments, which are expensed as incurred and not included in the measurement of operating lease assets and liabilities. </p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><ix:nonNumeric style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-size:1pt;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-size:2pt;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><a id="bm_5_Derivative_financial_instruments"></a><a id="Tc_hfcE-4JLhUuL0CJ5P4BbMw_1_2"></a><a id="Tc_ttxawouBTkO6i50ydgfJtg_1_5"></a><a id="Tc_0jQdLl_ESECYlmjuITYPfQ_2_2"></a><a id="Tc_ly8x22kBnkOvl6mVrzBXMQ_2_5"></a><a id="Tc_yoHmX-BY0UuuhQuYWuOD5A_3_2"></a><a id="Tc_dpJSKrCbtE-FgIfyPntUKw_4_0"></a><a id="Tc_YluRtmh5GUGu2SkwR7SOwg_4_2"></a><a id="Tc_Kqr23Vt8fUGZ4aG5id5m_A_4_5"></a><a id="Tc_s_TpFLF_q0GxjEVHJHmZdw_5_0"></a><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:DerivativeInstrumentsAndHedgingActivitiesDisclosureTextBlock" id="Tb_-uExJ5TU5kO0SFAOVr2z5Q" continuedAt="Tb_-uExJ5TU5kO0SFAOVr2z5Q_cont1" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">6. Derivative financial instruments</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">Many of the Company&#8217;s subsidiaries purchase and sell products in currencies other than their functional currencies. This subjects the Company to the risks associated with fluctuations in foreign currency exchange rates. The Company reduces this risk by utilizing natural hedging (e.g., offsetting receivables and payables in the same foreign currency) as well as by creating offsetting positions through the use of derivative financial instruments, primarily forward foreign exchange contracts typically with maturities of less than <ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_srt_RangeAxis_srt_MinimumMember_us-gaap_DerivativeInstrumentRiskAxis_us-gaap_ForeignExchangeForwardMember_MtOaQG-hHECV8njQqQfu7g" format="ixt-sec:durwordsen" name="us-gaap:DerivativeTermOfContract" id="Narr_1iboR22avUG32Q6dyr8ldA">60 days</ix:nonNumeric> (&#8220;economic hedges&#8221;), but no longer than <ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_srt_RangeAxis_srt_MaximumMember_us-gaap_DerivativeInstrumentRiskAxis_us-gaap_ForeignExchangeForwardMember_P15u7R7IVEeatpBDwETPeA" format="ixt-sec:durwordsen" name="us-gaap:DerivativeTermOfContract" id="Narr_XahVhrTxt0m014g22uffnA">one year</ix:nonNumeric>. The Company continues to have exposure to foreign currency risks to the extent they are not economically hedged. The Company adjusts any economic hedges to fair value through the consolidated statements of operations primarily within &#8220;Other (expense) income, net.&#8221; The fair value of forward foreign exchange contracts, which are based upon Level 2 criteria under the ASC 820 fair value hierarchy, are classified in the captions &#8220;Prepaid and other current assets&#8221; or &#8220;Accrued expenses and other,&#8221; as applicable, in the accompanying consolidated balance sheets as of December 28, 2019 and June 29, 2019. The Company&#8217;s master netting and other similar arrangements with various financial institutions related to derivative financial instruments allow for the right of offset. The Company&#8217;s policy is to present derivative financial instruments with the same counterparty as either a net asset or liability when the right of offset exists.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company generally does not hedge its investments in its foreign operations. The Company does not enter into derivative financial instruments for trading or speculative purposes and monitors the financial stability and credit standing of its counterparties.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company&#8217;s foreign currency exposure relates primarily to international transactions where the currency collected from customers can be different from the currency used to purchase from suppliers. The Company&#8217;s foreign operations transactions are denominated primarily in the following currencies: U.S. Dollar, Euro, British Pound, Japanese Yen, Chinese Yuan, Taiwan Dollar, Canadian Dollar and Mexican Peso. The Company also, to a lesser extent, has foreign operations transactions in other EMEA and Asia foreign currencies.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The fair values of forward foreign currency exchange contracts not receiving hedge accounting treatment recorded in the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheets are as follows:</p><ix:nonNumeric within the same line item in the consolidated statements of operations as the remeasurement of the underlying assets or liabilities being economically hedged.</p></ix:continuation><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><a id="bm_6_Commitments_and_contingencies"></a><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:CommitmentsAndContingenciesDisclosureTextBlock" id="Tb_poDUIiAIoE2FX7bFEz4vRQ" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">7. Commitments and contingencies</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">From time to time, the Company may become a party to, or be otherwise involved in various lawsuits, claims, investigations and other legal proceedings arising in the ordinary course of conducting its business. While litigation is subject to inherent uncertainties, management does not anticipate that any such matters will have a material adverse effect on the Company&#8217;s financial condition, liquidity or results of operations. </p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:13.7pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company is also currently subject to various pending and potential legal matters and investigations relating to compliance with governmental laws and regulations, including import/export and environmental matters. For certain of these matters it is not possible to determine the ultimate outcome, and the Company cannot reasonably estimate the maximum potential exposure or the range of possible loss for such matters due primarily to being in the early stages of the related proceedings and investigations. The Company currently believes that the resolution of such matters will not have a material adverse effect on the Company&#8217;s financial position or liquidity but could possibly be material to its results of operations in any one reporting period.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:13.7pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">As of December 28, 2019, and June 29, 2019, the Company had aggregate estimated liabilities of $<ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_6_29_2019_R1AOniZLZEq7MnH0mIe5cg" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:LossContingencyEstimateOfPossibleLoss" scale="6" id="Narr_H1dXx9qKJU-05qxWoLtk3A"><ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_12_28_2019_qrFIt1ADfEaVVPvPLTg9-w" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:LossContingencyEstimateOfPossibleLoss" scale="6" id="Narr_9nC0FBst3UarZC-Z3RReRg">14.7</ix:nonFraction></ix:nonFraction> million classified within accrued expenses and other for such compliance-related matters that were reasonably estimable as of such dates.</p></ix:nonNumeric><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><a id="bm_7_Income_taxes"></a><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock" id="Tb_NK0FRSy7HUK9cAEcBFv0Bw" continuedAt="Tb_NK0FRSy7HUK9cAEcBFv0Bw_cont1" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">8. Income taxes</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company&#8217;s effective tax rate on its income from continuing operations before taxes was <ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_pure_ROOYQs8DH0SppyZa338AWA" contextRef="Duration_9_29_2019_To_12_28_2019_FcUSeILTSU6ichjtcZQsfA" decimals="3" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:EffectiveIncomeTaxRateContinuingOperations" scale="-2" id="Narr_PUO6hfxCv0icDadNEnI_vg">56.8</ix:nonFraction>% in the second quarter of fiscal 2020. During the second quarter of fiscal 2020, the Company&#8217;s effective tax rate was unfavorably impacted primarily by (i) a valuation allowance against interest deduction deferred tax assets, partially offset by (ii) the mix of income in lower tax jurisdictions. </p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">During the second quarter of fiscal 2019, the Company&#8217;s effective tax rate on its income before income taxes from continuing operations of <ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_pure_ROOYQs8DH0SppyZa338AWA" contextRef="Duration_9_30_2018_To_12_29_2018_jgwAnWitmEyBjuoSKcM59w" decimals="3" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:EffectiveIncomeTaxRateContinuingOperations" scale="-2" id="Narr_j4LLQ4SSbkmsMmxNGG8e5w">43.3</ix:nonFraction>% was unfavorably impacted primarily by (i) an adjustment to the one-time mandatory deemed repatriation tax liability recorded under the requirements of recent tax law and regulation changes in the United States (the &#8220;Act&#8221;) and (ii) increases in unrecognized tax benefits, partially offset by (iii) the mix of income in lower tax jurisdictions, and (iv) the release of valuation allowances against deferred tax assets that were deemed to be realizable.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">For the first six months of fiscal 2020, the Company&#8217;s effective tax rate on its income before income taxes from continuing operations was a benefit of <ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_pure_ROOYQs8DH0SppyZa338AWA" contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" decimals="3" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:EffectiveIncomeTaxRateContinuingOperations" sign="-" scale="-2" id="Narr_GRsg-i6-KECASfSKMZFaqw">1.8</ix:nonFraction>%. The effective tax rate for the first six months of fiscal 2020 was favorably impacted primarily by (i) the release of unrecognized tax benefit reserves net of settlements and (ii) the mix of income in lower tax jurisdictions, partially offset by (iii) a valuation allowance against interest deduction deferred tax assets.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></ix:nonNumeric></div><div style="clear:both;margin-bottom:30pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">14</p></div></div>
<div style="background-color:#000000;clear:both;height:2pt;page-break-after:always;width:79.3%;border:0;margin:30pt 10.35% 30pt 10.35%;"></div><div style="max-width:100%;padding-left:10.35%;padding-right:10.35%;position:relative;"><div style="margin-top:21.6pt;min-height:41.75pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;margin:0pt 0pt 30pt 0pt;"><a href="#Toc"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;line-height:1.43;text-align:left;">Table of Contents</span></a></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;text-align:center;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">AVNET, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;text-align:center;margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS - (Continued)</b></p></div><div style="clear:both;max-width:100%;position:relative;"><ix:continuation id="Tb_NK0FRSy7HUK9cAEcBFv0Bw_cont1"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">During the first six months of fiscal 2019, the Company&#8217;s effective tax rate on its income before income taxes from continuing operations of <ix:nonFraction unitRef="Unit_Standard_pure_ROOYQs8DH0SppyZa338AWA" contextRef="Duration_7_1_2018_To_12_29_2018_Ne-vxy9uKUmgVLtJEFQzFQ" decimals="3" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:EffectiveIncomeTaxRateContinuingOperations" scale="-2" id="Narr_ptQbNbjLZkq1zrg9CiLvbA">33.1</ix:nonFraction>% was unfavorably impacted primarily by (i) an adjustment to the one-time mandatory deemed repatriation tax liability recorded under the requirements of the Act and (ii) increases in unrecognized tax benefits, partially offset by (iii) an adjustment to the provisional deferred tax impacts of the Act, (iv) the mix of income in lower tax jurisdictions, and (v) the release of valuation allowances against deferred tax assets that were deemed to be realizable.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">The Company&#8217;s effective tax rates in fiscal years 2019 and 2020 are based on the Company&#8217;s interpretation of tax regulations under the Act. The Company has made a policy election to account for any impacts of the Global Intangible Low Taxed Income (&#8220;GILTI&#8221;) tax as a period expense. The Company&#8217;s effective tax rate may change in future periods due to changes in U.S. tax regulations and the issuance of additional guidance related to the Act.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></ix:continuation><a id="bm_8_Pension_plan"></a><a id="_bd246086_7ffe_448a_8c20_c88ea474e528"></a><a id="Tc_aHCN51GfbUmd0o7EXQlpnA_1_2"></a><a id="Tc_b_fLAFz_sEOystTxkS3FDw_1_8"></a><a id="Tc_ezSZF8Hvv0udi4vWKwR7Ng_2_2"></a><a id="Tc_0s8TH35H-0-yFCqRNDqwDw_2_5"></a><a id="Tc_YNNoTwaM20CVfu42HP-IFw_2_8"></a><a id="Tc_HvU15Gnd3kefH75gaBOHmw_2_11"></a><a id="Tc_FLVx9a8Wz0SpExaMu4yGOQ_3_2"></a><a id="Tc_4htYZ8tToU6ncw9QAmiHVQ_3_5"></a><a id="Tc_Y8msfTCNnk2hd4ow7J89mQ_3_8"></a><a id="Tc_6qNCl_kSQEutO_pQpKyx5A_3_11"></a><a id="Tc_wLkib6mS-EeYPv2Ou_Ifqw_4_2"></a><a id="Tc_Hicea07kj0mwIeZEOLkM9Q_5_0"></a><a id="Tc_96ejNLR-mEa3h_Pd3xK13g_5_2"></a><a id="Tc_q-OvJPv3LEWv8ZiG4RZCMw_5_5"></a><a id="Tc_LPuDsfTM1UqNK_o4uDeLEQ_5_8"></a><a id="Tc_gMF7e45WWEO_ubraNHJLRw_5_11"></a><a id="Tc_oA45Xl58lEeMPX1HqDLF2g_6_0"></a><a id="Tc_HEUqgQt_8kiKTbPqHvjMqw_8_0"></a><a id="Tc_znUVmChchkq24mBnD-tMlA_9_0"></a><a id="Tc_TMVBKgpMNUiFTIiGegLXPQ_10_0"></a><a id="Tc_v02oISloAkC4LVdvjqNxLg_11_0"></a><a id="Tc_wqBtZhKzuEuzF4lICSFxRw_12_0"></a><a id="Tc__CDiJigHW06MtW_Y76ttWQ_14_0"></a><a id="Tc_X6znN_vhFUmMM0pk4OMKdw_14_2"></a><a id="Tc_TlXcAR4jlkeisr1ezzXsNA_14_5"></a><a id="Tc_R6Ym6bA8NkeTd_4CYyrMQA_14_8"></a><a id="Tc_xFwB2S3nP0itOtOuyElJ9Q_14_11"></a><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:PensionAndOtherPostretirementBenefitsDisclosureTextBlock" id="Tb_6zh3tS-JgUG81WaMG_RtxQ" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">9. unitRef="Unit_Standard_USD_klhF8qZsvk6de6VMcXPQiA" contextRef="As_Of_6_29_2019_R1AOniZLZEq7MnH0mIe5cg" decimals="-5" format="ixt:numdotdecimal" name="us-gaap:CashEquivalentsAtCarryingValue" scale="6" deposits.</p></ix:nonNumeric><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><a Segment information</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;">Electronic Components (&#8220;EC&#8221;) and Farnell (&#8220;Farnell&#8221;) are the Company&#8217;s reportable segments (&#8220;operating groups&#8221;). EC markets and sells semiconductors and interconnect, passive and electromechanical devices and integrated components to a diverse customer base serving many end-markets. Farnell distributes electronic components and related products to the electronic system design community utilizing multi-channel sales and marketing resources.</p><ix:nonNumeric contextRef="Duration_6_30_2019_To_12_28_2019_rMdYIGXsdEiqNET0JFA-EA" name="us-gaap:ScheduleOfSegmentReportingInformationBySegmentTextBlock" id="Tb_jFrLjbEumUyUkkDflUpggQ" continuedAt="Tb_jFrLjbEumUyUkkDflUpggQ_cont1" escape="true"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:23.75pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></ix:nonNumeric></ix:nonNumeric></div><div style="clear:both;margin-bottom:30pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">17</p></div></div>

style="max-width:100%;padding-left:10.35%;padding-right:10.35%;position:relative;"><div style="margin-top:21.6pt;min-height:41.75pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New id="Item_2_Managements_Discussion_and_Analy"></a><a id="Item_2"></a><table style="border-collapse:collapse;border:0;"><tr><td style="vertical-align:text-top;white-space:nowrap;width:54pt;padding:0pt;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">Item 2.</b></p></td><td style="padding:0pt;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;"><span style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Management&#8217;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;margin-left:0pt;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">For a description of the Company&#8217;s critical accounting policies and an understanding of the significant factors that influenced the Company&#8217;s performance during the quarter ended December 28, 2019, this <i style="font-style:italic;">Management&#8217;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</i> (&#8220;MD&amp;A&#8221;) should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements, including the related notes, appearing in Item&#160;1 of this Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q, as well as the Company&#8217;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the fiscal year ended June 29, 2019.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">There are references to the impact of foreign currency translation in the discussion of the Company&#8217;s results of operations. When the U.S. Dollar strengthens and the stronger exchange rates of the current year are used to translate the results of operations of Avnet&#8217;s subsidiaries denominated in foreign currencies, the resulting impact is a decrease in U.S. Dollars of reported results. Conversely, when the U.S. Dollar weakens and the weaker exchange rates of the current year are used to translate the results of operations of Avnet&#8217;s subsidiaries denominated in foreign currencies, the resulting impact is an increase in U.S. Dollars of reported results. In the discussion that follows, results excluding this impact, primarily for subsidiaries in Europe, the Middle East and Africa (&#8220;EMEA&#8221;) and Asia/Pacific (&#8220;Asia&#8221;), are referred to as &#8220;constant currency.&#8221;</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">In addition to disclosing financial results that are determined in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles in the U.S. (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;), the Company also discloses certain non-GAAP financial information, including:</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><table style="border-collapse:collapse;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;table-layout:fixed;text-align:justify;width:100%;border:0pt;"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"></td><td style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;vertical-align:text-top;white-space:nowrap;width:18pt;padding:0pt;">&#9679;</td><td style="padding:0pt;"><span style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;text-align:justify;">Sales adjusted for certain items that impact the year-over-year analysis, which includes the impact of certain acquisitions by adjusting Avnet&#8217;s prior periods to include the sales of acquired businesses, as if the acquisitions had occurred at the beginning of the earliest period presented. Sales taking into account these adjustments are referred to as &#8220;organic sales.&#8221;</span></td></tr></table><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;"><span style="margin-left:0pt;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><table style="border-collapse:collapse;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;table-layout:fixed;text-align:justify;width:100%;border:0pt;"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"></td><td style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;vertical-align:text-top;white-space:nowrap;width:18pt;padding:0pt;">&#9679;</td><td style="padding:0pt;"><span style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;text-align:justify;">Operating income excluding (i) restructuring, integration and other expenses (see </span><i style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:normal;text-align:justify;">Restructuring, Integration and Other Expenses</i><span style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;text-align:justify;"> in this MD&amp;A) and (ii) amortization of acquired intangible assets and other. Operating income excluding such amounts is referred to as &#8220;adjusted operating income.&#8221;</span></td></tr></table><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;"><span style="margin-left:0pt;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">The reconciliation of operating income to adjusted operating income is presented in the following table:</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span information is useful to readers to better assess and understand operating performance, especially when comparing results with prior periods or forecasting performance for future periods, primarily because management typically monitors the business both including and excluding these adjustments to GAAP results. Management also uses these non-GAAP measures to establish operational goals and, in many cases, for measuring performance for compensation purposes. However, any analysis of results on a non-GAAP basis should be used as a complement to, and in conjunction with, results presented in accordance with GAAP.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></div><div style="clear:both;margin-bottom:30pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">21</p></div></div>
<div style="background-color:#000000;clear:both;height:2pt;page-break-after:always;width:79.3%;border:0;margin:30pt 10.35% 30pt 10.35%;"></div><div style="max-width:100%;padding-left:10.35%;padding-right:10.35%;position:relative;"><div style="margin-top:21.6pt;min-height:41.75pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;line-height:1.43;margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 0pt;"><a href="#Toc"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;line-height:1.43;text-align:left;">Table of Contents</span></a></p></div><div style="clear:both;max-width:100%;position:relative;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">OVERVIEW</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Organization</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">Avnet, Inc. and its consolidated subsidiaries&#8217; (collectively, the &#8220;Company&#8221; or &#8220;Avnet&#8221;), is a global technology solutions company with an extensive ecosystem delivering design, product, marketing and supply chain expertise for customers at every stage of the product lifecycle. Avnet transforms ideas into intelligent solutions, reducing the time, cost and complexities of bringing products to market around the world. Founded in 1921 and incorporated in New York in 1955, the Company works with over 1,400 technology suppliers to serve 2.1 million customers in more than 140 countries.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">Avnet has two primary operating groups &#8212; Electronic Components (&#8220;EC&#8221;) and Farnell (&#8220;Farnell&#8221;). Both operating groups have operations in each of the three major economic regions of the world: (i) the Americas, (ii) EMEA and (iii) Asia. A summary of each operating group is provided in Note 13, &#8220;Segment information&#8221; to the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements included in this Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><a id="Results_of_operations"></a><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><b style="font-weight:bold;">Results of Operations</b></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">Sales of $4.53 billion were down 10.2% year over year and 9.4% in constant currency as compared to prior fiscal year second quarter sales of $5.05 billion. Both operating groups in all three regions contributed to the year-over-year decline in sales as the global industry-wide slowdown resulted in weaker year over year demand.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">Gross profit margin of 11.6% decreased 89 basis points compared to 12.5% in the second quarter of fiscal 2019 primarily due to gross profit margin declines in both operating groups. </p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:24pt;margin:0pt;">Operating income of $46.5 million decreased $49.6 million or 51.6% as compared to the second quarter of fiscal 2019. Operating income margin was 1.0% in the second quarter of fiscal 2020 as compared with a 1.9% in the second quarter of fiscal 2019. Both periods included amortization and restructuring, integration and other expenses. Excluding these expenses from both periods, adjusted operating income margin was 1.8% in the second quarter of fiscal 2020 as compared to 3.5% in the second quarter of fiscal 2019, a decline of 173 basis points. The decrease in adjusted operating income and adjusted operating income margin is primarily due to the decrease in sales and gross profit margin, partially offset by reductions in operating expenses from the Company&#8217;s restructuring and integration efforts.</p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;margin:0pt;"><span style="visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:justify;margin:0pt;"><span style="font-weight:bold;visibility:hidden;">&#8203;</span></p></div><div style="clear:both;margin-bottom:30pt;width:100%;"><p style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:10pt;text-align:center;margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">22</p></div></div>
